rComments: I took classes with him 1st and 2nd year, but it wasn't until my last class with him 4th year that I really learned to appreciate him. At first I thought he was just rambling purposelessly, but once I stopped trying to sift through his words methodologically and instead just sat back and listened, I started to really get the value of his lectures.

Mark Levene is a marvellous professor full of wisdom and enthusiasm for the text. Does he ramble tangentially? You bet. And it was always an instructive delight. Joyce, Orwell, Le Carr√©, Woolf, and numerous other authors were illuminated by his analysis. I left each lecture intellectually stimulated, full of ideas.

A very nice old man with funny/somewhat interesting stories about his life, but I'm finished the course now and I STILL don't know what it was about. Lectures have no structure and he just rambles on about sentences of the books that he likes and doesn't really say anything substantial.
